newsitem.title: USA: USWC CARB gasoline up with NYMEX, falling supply.
newsitem.headline: USWC CARB gasoline up with NYMEX, falling supply.

text.p: U.S. West Coast spot CARB gasoline prices rose Wednesday, lifted by stronger NYMEX energy prices and a drop in regional supply, traders said.
The American Petroleum Institute (API) reported early Wednesday that West Coast gasoline supplies fell 1.42 million barrels last week to 26.9 million.
NYMEX crude, which influences the price of West Coast products, settled 51 cents a barrel higher Wednesday, lifting by technical buying.
Players talked Los Angeles CARB-grade unleaded gasoline 1.75 cents higher than Tuesday at 76/77 cents a gallon.
Conventional gasoline in L.A. remained flat at 72/73 cents, with San Francisco grade also unchanged.
Distillates were steady, with CARB diesel in L.A. moving up about a penny to 73.50/74 cents, on talk of higher terminal prices.
